item.title: I did it! I kicked their scummy, evil asses!
item.description: This is a long story but tldr of the previous posts. Went to fight for the Ukrainians, left a paid rented apartment and told the landlords it's secured and I will be back in a couple months and resume living there. They scammed me, rented it out to someone else and pocketed what I paid. Afterwards they got convicted of fraud and I sued them.  --------- It's been a long fight but the court ruled in my favour today! I won! Their new lawyer screwed the pooch so hard today it's impossible not to laugh. He introduced a new piece of BS that was supposed to delay the whole thing again but it completely and utterly contradicted most of the previous ones... We caught it after it got submitted and nailed them in front of the judge who decided he's sick of it. Tore them a new one and ruled in my favour. I got rent and security deposit for the rest of the unrealized lease (14 months) plus court and lawyer costs. Plus rent on the place I had after that, lost wages and property. Their assets are frozen so they're gonna pay up if they want it or not.  Lawyer advises me that it's gonna take 6 months to a year cause courts are slow and overloaded so it's not over just now but it's a matter of time. It cost me 75k PLN (30 of which I still owe and can't delay paying off). I'm homeless and couch surfing until Christmas, then I got no idea what. My mental health is gone, my PTSD is so bad it's a wonder i didn't hurt anyone yet. I'm barely eating, maybe 800 calories a day to afford dog food. I'm a wreck... But I won and they got what's coming to them.  Still can't find stable employment, doing emergency plumbing and Uber  If anybody can help me last through this I would be forever grateful. I got a couple avenues for it.  I'm gonna go driving now, just wanted to share the good news Also if you live in the tricity area of Poland and have a cheap place to stay you're willing to rent for a while or work to offer, dm me please revolut: @jacek5f0e wise: @jacekn52 paypal: DM me Ko-fi: ko-fi.com/tyrcarter

item.title: 4 months post-op today! Recovery/health/scar/fitness update.
item.description:
This is for the folks who’ve been following along since I first posted about my Endo journey back at the end of the summer. Today marks 4 months since I had a total hysterectomy and had dozens of Endometriosis lesions and adhesions removed from my abdomen. I’ve had weekly doctors appointments since, as my entire body was infiltrated. I intermittently share about my medical stuff here, but today I want to focus on how far I’ve come in recovery.
In terms of muscle growth and body building, this might not be that impressive. But I’m fucking proud of how far I’ve come in 4 months, both physically and psychologically. For the folks who’ve been here a lot, you probably bore witness to my very embarrassing crash out the month following surgery. I was in a car accident and that certainly didn’t help. But mostly, I learned just how vital movement/lifting/fitness is to my mental health. I wasn’t able to lift or move at all for 8 weeks, and I wasn’t able to lift more than 20lbs for another 4 weeks.
I’ve spent the past 4 weeks slowly and carefully getting myself back to where I was before surgery. I’ve been listening to my body and to my incisions, as they still ache and get tender when I really try to push myself. I’m not yet back to where I want to be, but I’m pretty happy with how far I’ve come.
After so many years lost to being sick, I don’t want to lose a single second more if I can help it. I’ve changed a lot about my life and how I spend my time these past few months. I think a silver lining of being chronically ill, is that you realize just how fucking precious your time is when you feel well. And you want to make the absolute most of every moment. I still have pain and it’s still intense. But it doesn’t debilitate as much, and I feel that movement works for me to help overcome it. Lifting is where I meditate and can actually be at peace in my body.
Life is still scary. My apartment is still gross and expensive. I’m still scraping by. But I’ve figured out how to find and choose joy. I’ve learned that whimsy is radical. I feel more in control, and more able to accept when I’m not. Life is weird and beautiful and scary and hilarious. The horrors will always persist, but so will I. And I will choose joy in spite of them. Much love, from Bri.
